ainly Scottish variant of Irish   Daly  .","Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Dally   2, a cognate of 3 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Daly","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Kieran, Dermot, Brigid, Aileen, Declan, Finbarr, Fintan, Aidan, Brennan, Bridie, Cathal.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Dálaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Dálach</i>’, a personal name based on <i>dál</i> (modern <i>dáil</i>) ‘meeting, assembly’.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Dally   2."]},{"name":"Alyea","meanings":["Americanized form of French <b>D'Ailly</b> or   Dailly  . Compare   Allee   2 and   Elyea  .","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors (along with several variants, including <i>Allée</i>, and the original form <i>d'Ailly</i>). The Huguenot ancestor was Nicolas d'Ailly, who came from France to NY <i>c.</i> 1682 via the Netherlands and England and died in NJ <i>c.</i> 1700."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gilbert d'Oilly was born about 1014, in Calvados, France as the son of Sir Osmond bassett D'oilly. He had at least 1 son with Frances Barney. He died in 1060, in France, at the age of 47."},"et":{"ABT 1014–1060":"umbes 1014–1060","1014–1060":"1014–1060","1008–1060":"1008–1060","1040–1115":"1040–1115","0990–1025":"0990–1025","1008":"100